SIMPLE: subsidiary
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Subsidiary
<hw>Sub*sid"i*a*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>subsidiarius</ets>: cf. F. <ets>subsidiaire</ets>. See
<er>Subsidy</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Furnishing aid; assisting;
auxiliary; helping; tributary; especially, aiding in an inferior
position or capacity; <as>as, a <ex>subsidiary</ex>
stream</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Chief ruler and principal head everywhere, not suffragant and
<qex>subsidiary</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Florio.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They constituted a useful <qex>subsidiary</qex> testimony of
another state of existence.</q> <rj><qau>Coleridge.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to a subsidy; constituting a
subsidy; being a part of, or of the nature of, a subsidy; <as>as,
<ex>subsidiary</ex> payments to an ally</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>George the Second relied on his <qex>subsidiary</qex>
treaties.</q> <rj><qau>Ld. Mahon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Subsidiary</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Subsidiary
<hw>Sub*sid"i*a*ry</hw>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Subsidiaries</plw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>.</plu> <def>One who, or that
which, contributes aid or additional supplies; an assistant; an
auxiliary.</def> <rj><au>Hammond.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Subsidize</ent>⟦br⟧
